If a dictionary is defined to contain a sub-dictionary, for example:

```
        subdict = {'a': 'A'}
        dct = {'sub': subdict}
```

If the `_merge_dict` method is used to merge another dict into it, and the other dict has a sub-dictionary of the same name, then the original sub-dictionary also gets modified.

For example the following test:

```
        subdict = {'a': 'A'}
        dct = {'sub': subdict}
        overrides = {'sub': {'b': 'B'}}
        _merge_dict(dct, overrides)
        self.assertEqual(subdict, {'a': 'A'})
```

fails:

```
>       self.assertEqual(subdict, {'a': 'A'})
E       AssertionError: {'a': 'A', 'b': 'B'} != {'a': 'A'}
E       - {'a': 'A', 'b': 'B'}
E       + {'a': 'A'}
```

This may be the expected behavior in terms of how python handles dictionaries, but I don't think this is what was expected when this code was written.
